@page "/installation"
<PageTitle>Installation - Saascade Docs</PageTitle>

<h1 id="installation">Installation</h1>

<div class="doc-layout">

<main class="documentation">

    <TechCard>
        <section class="card">

            <h2 id="nuget-package">NuGet Package</h2>

            <p class="subtitle">
                Install the Saascade Blazor Components library via NuGet or the .NET CLI.
            </p>

            <hr />

            <h3>.NET CLI</h3>
            <pre><code>dotnet add package Saascade.Blazor.Components</code></pre>

            <h3>Package Manager</h3>
            <pre><code>Install-Package Saascade.Blazor.Components</code></pre>

        </section>
    </TechCard>

    <TechCard>
        <section class="card">

            <h2 id="add-imports">Add Imports</h2>

            <p>
                Add the following to your <code>_Imports.razor</code> so components are available
                across all pages without per-file using directives:
            </p>

            <pre><code>@@using Saascade.Blazor.Components</code></pre>

        </section>
    </TechCard>

    <TechCard Tech="bootstrap">
        <section class="card">

            <h2 id="install-bootstrap">Bootstrap 5 Setup</h2>

            <p class="subtitle">Bootstrap 5 Installation</p>

            <hr />

            <p>
                Register the Bootstrap 5 design system in Program.cs using the VanillaBootstrap5
                preset. Then add the DesignSystemStylesheetReferences component to your index.html
                or App.razor layout — it automatically injects the Bootstrap CDN stylesheet link,
                so you do not need to manage the link tag manually.
            </p>

        </section>
    </TechCard>

    <TechCard Tech="daisyui">
        <section class="card">

            <h2 id="install-daisyui">DaisyUI Setup</h2>

            <p class="subtitle">DaisyUI Installation</p>

            <hr />

            <p>
                Register the DaisyUI design system in Program.cs using the DaisyUI preset.
                DaisyUI requires Tailwind CSS to be configured in your project. The
                DesignSystemStylesheetReferences component includes the necessary CDN reference
                for the DaisyUI stylesheet so components render correctly without manual
                stylesheet management.
            </p>

        </section>
    </TechCard>

    <TechCard Tech="basecoat">
        <section class="card">

            <h2 id="install-basecoat">Basecoat Setup</h2>

            <p class="subtitle">Basecoat Installation</p>

            <hr />

            <p>
                Register the Basecoat design system in Program.cs using the Basecoat preset.
                Like DaisyUI, Basecoat is built on Tailwind CSS. Add the
                DesignSystemStylesheetReferences component to your layout to include the Basecoat
                stylesheet automatically. Ensure your Tailwind configuration includes the Basecoat
                plugin or CDN build for the utility classes to resolve correctly.
            </p>

        </section>
    </TechCard>

</main>

<TableOfContents Items="@([
    new TocItem("installation", "Installation"),
    new TocItem("nuget-package", "NuGet Package", 2),
    new TocItem("add-imports", "Add Imports", 2),
    new TocItem("install-bootstrap", "Bootstrap 5 Setup", 2),
    new TocItem("install-daisyui", "DaisyUI Setup", 2),
    new TocItem("install-basecoat", "Basecoat Setup", 2)
])" />

</div>
